There are two general approaches to assessing functional con-
nectivity. The task-based fMRI approach measures correlated activ-
ity that arises when cortical areas are coactivated in the service of
performing some function, such as inhibiting a prepotent response
in a go/no-go paradigm. In resting state fMRI, subjects are imaged
“at rest,” meaning they are not asked to perform any task concur-
rently. The resting brain spontaneously generates large-amplitude,
low-frequency blood oxygen level dependent signal oscillations.
These oscillations are correlated within functionally plausible
networks and are assumed to reﬂect a history of coactivation
leading to synaptic potentiation (34). Both approaches have
been applied to the study of ADHD. Again, the technique is
rapidly evolving, and to date, very few studies of ADHD have
applied the same

