present. An excellent, comprehensive review (11) encapsulates the
heterogeneity of these studies and the complexity of their results,
which we summarize brieﬂy in Tables 2 and 3. We focus our discus-
sion here on ﬁndings that might inform two key questions concern-
ing the DTI results described in the preceding text. First, do struc-
tural connectivity deﬁcits have any impact on functional properties
of frontostriatal networks? And second, do connectivity changes
correlate with clinical symptoms?
The Default Mode Network in ADHD
For years, most fMRI studies assessed changes in brain activity
that occur while performing some task of interest relative to a
baseline condition, such as visual ﬁxation. More recently, investiga-
tors have recognized that a distinct set of structures tend to be
active at baseline—and relatively deactivated during task perfor-
mance—reﬂecting a default mode of spontaneous activity in the
brain at rest. This default mode network (DMN) comprises midline
structures including the precuneus and posterior cingulate cortex
and the ventromedial PFC (35). Spontaneous low-frequency oscil-
lationsinthesestructuresarehighlycorrelated(36),andthisactivity
has been linked to non–goal-directed, introspective, self-referen-
tial processes akin to “mind wandering” (37) as well as to processes
mediating alertness to changes in the external and internal envi-
ronment (38). Interestingly, DMN activity is anticorrelated with lat-
eral PFC activity during executive function and attentional tasks
(36), raising the possibility that executive function deﬁcits might
arise from a failure to suppress DMN activity during task perfor-
mance.
Castellanos et al. (39) tested this hypothesis by acquiring resting
state fMRI scans in 20 adults meeting lifetime criteria for combined
type ADHD and 20 healthy control subjects. As expected, in both
control subjects and ADHD patients, DMN activity was anticorre-
lated with activity in the dorsal ACC, which plays an important role
in regulating attention and cognitive control (see following). How-
ever, this relationship was much weaker in the ADHD group, con-
sistent with a failure to suppress non–goal-directed DMN activity in
ADHD during tasks requiring cognitive control. They also observed
reduced functional connectivity among precuneus, ventromedial
PFC, and other DMN structures in the ADHD group. Five other
studies have reported similar results (24,40–43), but a sixth did not
(44). Several other resting state fMRI studies (24,45–50) have re-
ported ﬁndings that are generally consistent with these but use
varied analytic methods that complicate direct comparisons be-
tween reports. These are described in more detail in Tables 2 and 3.
However, these results provide preliminary evidence to suggest
that ADHD is associated with functional as well as structural con-
nectivity changes, although it remains unclear whether alterations
in these two domains are related.
