Functional Correlates of Frontostriatal Connectivity
Deﬁcits in ADHD
Anotherimportantquestionraisedbytheaforementionedstud-
ies is whether functional connectivity deﬁcits have any direct im-
pact on symptoms. Establishing causation is a major challenge in
imaging studies of human subjects. One way to tackle this problem
is by asking whether medications that treat symptoms also amelio-
rate connectivity deﬁcits. Rubia et al. (51) examined methylpheni-
date effects on PFC function and attention by combining functional
connectivity analysis and task-based fMRI during a rewarded con-
tinuous performance task, assessing the effects of reward process-
ing on attentional control. Previously unmedicated ADHD patients
made more errors and showed reduced frontostriatal connectivity
and task-related activity in ventrolateral prefrontal structures,
among others. They also showed enhanced reward-related activity
in orbitofrontal cortex, implicating both frontostriatal and meso-
corticolimbic circuits in the deﬁcits they observed. Methylpheni-
date ameliorated many of these deﬁcits, increasing frontostriatal
connectivity and normalizing reward processing and performance.
Similarly, Peterson et al. (41) found that methylphenidate normal-
ized the deﬁcits of ADHD patients in suppressing DMN activity
during performance of a Stroop task by normalizing the diminished
inﬂuenceofventralanteriorcingulatecortexonlateralPFC.Aspects
of this interaction predicted methylphenidate effects on ADHD
symptoms scales. Three other studies in children (40,51,52) and one
in adults (53) have reported functional connectivity deﬁcits in
ADHD subjects during performance of varied tasks requiring cogni-
tive control (see Table 2 for details). Together, these studies show
that at least some functional connectivity deﬁcits in ADHD are not
ﬁxed and can be mitigated acutely by stimulant treatment. They
also lend indirect support to the hypothesis that connectivity deﬁ-
cits might contribute to symptoms of inattention and altered re-
ward processing. Of course, correlated changes need not reﬂect
causation. Are connectivity deﬁcits in ADHD a cause of symptoms
or just another end point of a common etiologic mechanism? We
conclude by considering these two possibilities.
Causes and Consequences of Connectivity Deﬁcits in
ADHD
Several lines of evidence support the hypothesis that connectiv-
ity deﬁcits might contribute directly to inattention, impulsivity, and
other ADHD symptoms. Attention-deﬁcit/hyperactivity disorder
