has been conceptualized as a disease of impaired executive func-
tion and of deﬁcient inhibitory control in particular (4), processes
subservedbyafrontostriatal network including lateral PFC, anterior
cingulate cortex, and posterior parietal cortex, with inputs from the
dorsal striatum and cerebellum (Figure 2). Lateral PFC has been
implicated in regulating task-relevant representations of stimulus
information and striatal stimulus-response mappings (54,55), pos-
sibly in response to signals from anterior cingulate and posterior
parietal areas that signal the need for top-down control by detect-
ing processing conﬂicts in various forms (56–58). Inputs from the
striatum and cerebellum have also been implicated in regulating
behavior on the basis of information about the frequency and tim-
ing of events, respectively (10). Other work has emphasized the
importance of catecholaminergic projections to the ventral stria-
tum, PFC, and limbic structures, including the hippocampus,
amygdala, and orbitofrontal cortex. Dysfunction in this mesocorti-
colimbic network has been linked to so-called “hot” executive func-
tiondeﬁcits(6),including emotional dysregulation, impulsivity, and
the processing of reward and salience (59,60).
Reﬁned connectivity is associated with and might be an impor-
tant cause of enhanced cognitive control in typically developing
children. Diffusion tensor imaging studies have shown that diffu-
sion becomes more restricted with age in frontostriatal white mat-
ter tracts throughout the teen years (61,62). Prefrontal white matter
integrity, in turn, was associated with improved cognitive skills,
including enhanced reading scores (63) and increased working
memory with age in adolescence (64). Importantly, DTI measures of
structural connectivity also predicted performance on a go/no-go
cognitivecontroltaskindependentlyofage(Figure3)(62),suggest-
ing that individual connectivity differences have important func-
tional correlates. Likewise, white matter maturation is associated
with increasingly focused recruitment of prefrontal structures dur-
ing inhibitory tasks (65–68). Together, these results suggest that
functional disconnections within frontostriatal and mesocortico-
limbic networks might represent a signiﬁcant pathway to disease
symptoms in ADHD. They might disrupt control mechanisms by
interfering with the detection of different forms of conﬂict, the
recruitment of top-down bias signals, or the processing of reward
and salience. These unique but not mutually exclusive possibilities
warrant further investigation.
Alternatively, disrupted connectivity and symptoms might arise
incidentally from common etiologic mechanisms. Structural con-
