nectivity changes, in particular, might be a marker of a history of
dysregulated plasticity. Maturation of axonal white matter tracts is
understood to be intimately linked to a co-occurring, progressive,
experience-dependent synaptic pruning process that continues
throughout adolescence in the human PFC (69–72). Even in the
adult brain, experience-dependent structural remodeling contin-
ues: in vivo imaging studies indicate that dendritic spines—the
postsynaptic sites of most excitatory inputs—undergo continuous
remodeling (73–75), and some studies suggest that these changes
might be associated with axonal remodeling (76).
Importantly, known environmental risk factors for ADHD might
lead independently to many of the same structural connectivity
deﬁcits, even in subjects without ADHD. Childhood lead exposure,
even at levels signiﬁcantly lower than those considered safe by the
Centers for Disease Control, has not only been linked to ADHD risk
(77,78)butalsotowidespreadirregularitiesindiffusionmeasuresof
white matter integrity that persist into adulthood, affecting fronto-
striatal tracts diffusely, regardless of ADHD diagnosis (79). Likewise,
low birth weight confers a signiﬁcantly elevated risk for developing
ADHD (80) and is independently associated with disruptions in
white matter tracts, occurring even in subjects who did not go on to
develop ADHD (28).
These changes might occur through a direct effect on oligoden-
drocytes or indirectly, by altering plasticity mechanisms. Lead ex-
posure is a relatively well-studied cause of ADHD-like symptoms
that illustrates this point well. In rats, lead exposure causes a 15%–
20% decrease in the expression of myelin associated glycoproteins
and myelin oligodendrocyte glycoproteins, disrupts the axonal
sheath, and delays differentiation of rat oligodendrocyte progeni-
tor cells in vitro (81,82). At the molecular level, lead interferes with
neuronal plasticity mechanisms, possibly by disrupting glutamate
release, N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor functioning, and long-term
potentiation (83). Toxic lead exposures might cause dendritic spine
loss by mimicking calcium and excessively activating protein kinase
C (84), an important molecular mediator of synaptic plasticity, lead-
ing to actin destabilization and spine elimination in vitro (85). In
support of this hypothesis, a protein kinase C inhibitor was shown
to prevent chronic stress-related spine loss in PFC (86). Importantly,
overlapping structural connectivity deﬁcits have been reported in
DTI studies of other conditions that involve dysregulated synaptic
plasticity, including pediatric bipolar disorder (22), schizophrenia
(20), and epilepsy (31), indicating that these white matter irregular-
ities are not speciﬁc to ADHD and do not necessarily lead to ADHD
symptoms.
Finally, it is worth noting that genetic factors that have been
implicated in the etiology of ADHD might also lead independently
to white matter irregularities by disrupting synaptic plasticity. As
discussed in more detail in a recent review (87), three genome-wide
association studies of ADHD failed to provide consistent evidence
of overlapping regions of linkage. However, multiple ADHD candi-
date-gene studies have implicated polymorphisms in genes regu-
lating dopaminergic transmission, including those coding for the
dopamine transporter (88–90) and the D4 dopamine receptor
(91,92) as well as other dopamine receptor subtypes and enzymes
involved in dopamine synthesis and breakdown, including dopa-
mine beta hydroxylase, tyrosine hydroxylase, catechol-O-methyl-
transferase, and monoamine oxidase A (87). Although genes regu-
latingotherneuromodulatorysystemshavealsobeenimplicatedin
candidate gene studies (87), the dopaminergic system warrants
special consideration here.
Dopamine is believed to play a critical role in regulating synaptic
plasticity during development (93–95). Altered dopaminergic sig-
naling has been linked to deﬁcits in DTI measures of white matter
integrity, especially in frontostriatal tracts. Prenatal cocaine expo-
sure, for example, has been linked to reduced prefrontal white
matter anisotropy (96), and a catechol-O-methyltransferase poly-
morphism that might increase synaptic dopamine availability has
been associated with similar white matter irregularities (97). Al-
though molecular, genetic, and pharmacological studies have fre-
quently linked ADHD to a hypodopaminergic state, others suggest
the opposite: striatal dopamine transporter availability, for exam-
ple, was reported to be increased (98), decreased (99,100), or unaf-
fected (101) in various studies of ADHD patients. The study by
Thomason et al. (97) serves to emphasize that alterations in dopa-
minergic signaling—leading either to excess or deﬁciency—might
disrupt physiological plasticity mechanisms and prefrontal white
matter integrity, independent of ADHD diagnosis. This interpreta-
tion is consistent with evidence from rodent and nonhuman pri-
mate models highlighting the importance of an optimal, moderate
level of catecholaminergic signaling for performance in prefrontal
cortical learning and memory paradigms (102,103).
Collectively, these studies indicate that white matter micro-
structural abnormalities are not speciﬁc to ADHD, do not necessar-
ily lead to ADHD symptoms, and might arise from multiple etiolo-
gies that have been implicated in disrupting synaptic plasticity.
Thus, structural connectivity deﬁcits in ADHD might be better-
viewed as a nonspeciﬁc marker of a history of dysregulated plastic-
ity arising secondary to a common etiologic mechanism than as a
pathophysiological pathway that leads necessarily and speciﬁcally
to ADHD.
Summary and Conclusions
This review highlights several important ﬁndings from DTI and
functional connectivity studies of ADHD as well as the difﬁculties
inherentindrawingﬁrmconclusionsfromthisrapidlyevolvingﬁeld
of study. Replication and cross-study comparisons have been com-
plicated by the multitude of analytic techniques and measure-
ments employed in various studies. Despite this heterogeneity,
some consistent results are emerging. Diffusion tensor imaging
studies indicate that ADHD is signiﬁcantly associated with struc-
tural connectivity deﬁcits in functionally relevant white matter
tracts, especially the SLF and the anterior corona radiata that carry
frontostriatal projections. Functional connectivity and resting state
fMRI studies are more difﬁcult to compare, but they have also be-
gun to yield plausible pathophysiological mechanisms by which
altered connectivity might lead to symptoms of inattention and
impulsivity, possibly by altering interactions between frontostriatal
attentional networks and a DMN active during non–goal-oriented,
introspective processes. Both performance deﬁcits and functional
connectivity changes in relevant networks are ameliorated acutely
by stimulants, suggesting that functional connectivity deﬁcits
might play an important role in generating symptoms. In contrast,
structural connectivity deﬁcits are persistent and might arise be-
cause of one or more core deﬁcits leading to dysregulated modula-
tion of cortical plasticity in the developing brain. This hypothesis
highlights potential avenues for novel treatments aimed at restor-
ing physiological patterns of synaptic plasticity that are already a
subject of interest in other areas of psychiatry.
Interestingly, functional connectivity deﬁcits might also prove
useful for diagnosis. Multiple studies have shown that patterns of
functional connectivity identiﬁed by resting state fMRI are highly
consistent and replicable in different groups of subjects and as-
sessed by different investigators (38,104,105). A recent study of
over 1400 subjects at 35 international sites revealed a highly con-
sistent architecture of connectivity as well as consistent sites of
